                        Stuart
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1948v07</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d285</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">285</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1948-07-21T02:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1948-07-21T02:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-07-21T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-07-21T02:00:00-05:00" n="285" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.002/7–2148: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-07-21T16:00:00+09:00">July 21, 1948—4 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 21—10:34 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1334. Air Nanking is full of rumors as to ways and means of persuading
                    Generalissimo to change his way or to make his regime more effective (Shanghai’s
                    1627, July 20, repeated Nanking 1316<note n="12" xml:id="d285fn12">Not printed;
                        reference was made therein to “rumor that US Government has urged
                        Generalissimo to retire in favor of 7-man regency board.”
                        (893.002/7–2048)</note>). No one in Embassy has urged Generalissimo to
                    retire in favor Regency as suggested Shanghai’s telegram.</p>
                <p>Sent Dept 1334, repeated Shanghai 644.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
